VEVENT.DESCRIPTION: Write a "catalog poem" in imitation of Section 15 of "Song of M
VEVENT.EXTRADESCRIPTION: yself" depicting the teeming world you inhabit. Be as encompassing and inclusive as you can be as, line by line, you describe in precise detail the various people (and other creatures) that make up your environment. Include what’s going on indoors as well as outdoors. Think of it as a panorama of your place and time. Readers of your poem ages from now should be able to tell what it feels like to be alive in New York in the fall of the year 2022. Keep commentary to a minimum (as Whitman does), but let your description convey feeling when appropriate. Conclude, as Whitman does, with a sense of things coming to a rest. Minimum: 25 lines. (More on this as we talk about this and other sections of "Song of Myself" next week. Get started on this over the weekend; due next Friday, the 23rd of September!)

VEVENT.DESCRIPTION: At the end of section 51, Whitman asks two questions: "Will you
VEVENT.EXTRADESCRIPTION: speak before I am gone? Will you prove already too late?" What does he expect us to say? What does he feel (fear?) we might be late for? Is the clue in the last line of the poem whose fine word is you? ("I stop some where waiting for you")  I'll make your comments visible. Talk to each other. Agree, disagree, elaborate.

VEVENT.DESCRIPTION: Below are listed three sections of “Song of Myself”
VEVENT.EXTRADESCRIPTION: ober 7th--SEE INSTRUCTIONS) that we have not discussed. Please reread each of them and make sure you understand what the central concern of each one is. Because there’s a lot of repetition in the poem, you might be tempted to think Whitman’s simply saying the same old thing over and over again. For this reason, look closely at the imagery or metaphoric language that make each of these sections distinctive. Think about the underlying logic of each section, how each grouping of lines fits together to convey a more or less coherent experience or idea. You should be able not only to offer a coherent interpretation of the section, but also articulate how it fits into the poem as a whole.  Here’s what to expect: When you come to class, you’ll be assigned a section at random. I’ll ask a specific question about each one. You’ll write a coherent essay in response. Chance favors the prepared mind.(Louis Pasteur) You may bring:  Your annotated copy of Whitman Three index cards with notes, front and back Reread:   Section 25 Section 32 Section 43

VEVENT.DESCRIPTION: Answer these questions in your notebook for discussion. I will
VEVENT.EXTRADESCRIPTION: not collect them, but I will notice if you've done the work!  1. What do you come to understand about Edna from the account of her crushes and romantic interests before her marriage to Leonce? (Chapter 7)  2. What do you make of the way Edna experiences the piano-playing of Mademoiselle Reisz and music in general? (Chapter 9)  3. Lying in her hammock as Robert sits silently beside her,  Edna is said to be experiencing "the first throbbings of desire." How does her experience in the water (which leads up to this moment) symbolically relate to these feelings? What has she undergone that brings her to this "pregnant" moment? (Chapter 10)

VEVENT.DESCRIPTION: How do you understand the final page of Gatsby? Why does Nick's
VEVENT.EXTRADESCRIPTION: reverie--looking out on the water from the beach below Gatsby's estate--blossom into an image of Dutch sailors? How do you understand the way history and desire--the past, the present and the future--converge here? Why are we included in his vision? What of "wonder"? What place does it have in the unfolding of the vision? Do images here mirror images elsewhere in the novel? How? These questions are meant to be suggestive and generative, not prescriptive. Settle on an observation and answer in your own way. Just a few sentences. N. B. These discussion questions do not evaporate into the ether. I read them and, as you've noticed, refer to ones that stay with me in our discussions in class. The more you put your thoughts down in writing, the more skillful writer you will become. Practice, practice, practice!
